{"title_page": "Bircham International University", "text_new": "{{Globalize|1=article|2=United States|date=February 2020}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name=Bircham International University\n|image=File:Bircham-University.jpg\n|established=1992\n|city=[[Madrid]]\n|country=[[Spain]]\n|type=[[Educational accreditation|Unaccredited]] distance learning\n|president=Deric Bircham\n|vice-president=Laurence Cheng Wen\n|head_label=CEO\n|head=William Martin\n|website={{URL|http://www.bircham.edu}}\n}}\n[[File:Bircham International University Madrid Office.jpg|thumb|Bircham International University office in Madrid]]\n\n'''Bircham International University''' is a private, [[educational accreditation|unaccredited]]<ref name=\"ODA2013\">{{cite news |url=http://www.oregonstudentaid.gov/oda-degree-authorization-academic-unauthorized-Invalid.aspx |title=Unauthorized Schools and Invalid Degrees |publisher=[[Oregon State Office of Degree Authorization]] |access-date=4 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509021211/http://oregonstudentaid.gov/oda-degree-authorization-academic-unauthorized-Invalid.aspx |archive-date=9 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MainDepartLisAcr\">{{cite web |title=List of Non-Accredited Post-Secondary Schools |url=http://www.maine.gov/doe/highered/nonaccredited/list/b.html |publisher=Maine Department of Education |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref>\ninstitution of [[distance-learning]] higher education. It is registered in [[Spain]] and [[Delaware]], and formerly operated from [[the Bahamas]].<ref name=\"Delaware3169search\">{{cite web |title=Delaware Company Search 3169257 |url=https://delecorp.delaware.gov/tin/GINameSearch.jsp |publisher=Delaware.gov |access-date=29 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106214416/https://delecorp.delaware.gov/tin/GINameSearch.jsp |archive-date=6 January 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBIU was founded by Deric Bircham, William Martin, and Bircham's adopted son, Laurence Cheng Wen.<ref name=\"CredentialWatchBarrett\">{{cite web |last=Barrett |first=Stephen |title=A Skeptical Look at Bircham International University |url=http://www.credentialwatch.org/reports/bircham.shtml |publisher=Credential Watch |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> According to its website,<ref name=\"BIULegalHistory\">{{cite web |title=BIU Legal History |url=http://www.bircham.us/foundations/biu-legal-history.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226035457/http://www.bircham.us/foundations/biu-legal-history.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 December 2013 |publisher=BIU Forum |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> Bircham was established in Europe in 1992<ref>{{cite book |last1=Seneca |first1=Kristofer |title=Guide to Earning Law and Law-Related Degrees Nontraditionally |date=2009 |publisher=Lulu |isbn=978-0-557-10593-9<!-- |access-date=27 June 2014-->}}</ref> and is also registered in Delaware (United States), Spain, and the Bahamas. [[John Bear]], authority on [[distance education]], wrote in the 2003 edition of ''Bears' Guide to Earning Degrees by Distance Learning'' that Bircham's listed \"delegation addresses [are] in Spain, England, United States (a [[Mail Boxes Etc.]] in Miami, Florida), Bahamas, Taiwan, China, Mexico, Argentina, Venezuela, Ecuador, Peru, Bolivia, Columbia, and New Zealand.\" ''Bear's Guide'' states that \"the offices in England and the Bahamas were strictly administrative and did not serve students.\"<ref name=\"bear\">{{cite book|last=Bear|first=John|url=|title=Bears' Guide to Earning Degrees by Distance Learning|date=2003|publisher=Ten Speed Press|isbn=1-58008-431-1|location=|page=}}<!--|access-date= 7 July 2015--></ref>\n\nBircham acquired  Oxford International College in 2000.<ref name=\"BirchRevisted\">{{cite web |last=Bear |first=John |title=Bircham International University revisited |url=http://www.degreeinfo.com/general-distance-learning-discussions/45894-bircham-international-university-revisited.html |publisher=Degree Info |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"OxfordUK\">{{cite web |title=Oxford International College in the UK |url=http://www.bircham.net/uk-companies-house.html |publisher=BIU Human Network |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Oxford College Dissolved |url=http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk |website=UK Companies House |access-date=2 November 2014 |location=3656298}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation status ==\n\nBIU's website presents a list of accreditations and memberships,<ref name=\"BIUworldreferences\">{{cite web |title=Bircham International University World References |url=http://www.bircham.net/biu-references/world-references.html |publisher=BIU Human Network |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> but none of them are from an educational accreditation body recognized by the countries where it operates.<ref name=\"ODA2013 \" />{{better source|date=January 2015}}\n\nSources explicitly listing Bircham as \"unaccredited\" include the Maine Department of Education and the Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board, which state that Bircham has \"No degree-granting authority from Spain (American Association of Collegiate Registrars and Admissions Officers [AACRAO] evaluation).\"<ref name=\"MDoEducatList\">{{cite web |title=List of Non-Accredited Post-Secondary Schools \u2013 B |url=http://www.maine.gov/doe/highered/nonaccredited/list/b.html |publisher=Maine Department of Education |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"TexasIllegaDegree\">{{cite web |title=Institutions Whose Degrees are Illegal to Use in Texas |url=http://www.thecb.state.tx.us/index.cfm?objectid=EF4C3C3B-EB44-4381-6673F760B3946FBB |publisher=Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board |access-date=29 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712033711/http://www.thecb.state.tx.us/index.cfm?objectid=EF4C3C3B-EB44-4381-6673F760B3946FBB |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Oregon Office of Degree Authorization considers BIU an unaccredited foreign degree supplier.<ref name=\"ODA2013 \" />\n\nBIU describes itself as a practitioner of non-formal education. While it operates legally under Spanish law, it is not formally recognized by the [[Ministry of Education (Spain)|Ministry of Education of Spain]].<ref name=\"BirchRevisted \" /><ref name=\"DegreeDiscussion21\">{{cite web |last=Bear |first=John |title=Bircham International University revisited |url=http://www.degreediscussion.com/forums/viewtopic.php?f=2&t=9556 |publisher=Degree Discussion |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ZegabiEANKenya\">{{cite web |title=Bircham International University in Kenya |url=http://www.zegabi.com/articles/?p=5805 |publisher=Zegabi East Africa News |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> Because BIU is unaccredited, its degrees and credits might not be acceptable to employers or other institutions. Use of its degree titles may be illegal in some jurisdictions.<ref name=\"TexasIllegaDegree \" />\n\n== Reception ==\n\nIn 2003, South Florida's ''CityLink'' magazine reported that Oregon education officials said that Bircham was \"totally bogus\".<ref name=\"CityLinksMagArchive\">{{cite news |last=Paola |first=Jim Di |title=Schoolhouse crock |url=http://www.citylinkmagazine.com/archives/101503coverstory.html |access-date=29 May 2014 |newspaper=City Link Magazine |date=15 October 2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402214223/http://www.citylinkmagazine.com/archives/101503coverstory.html |archive-date=2 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, the [[Secretariat of Public Education]] (SEP) of Mexico issued a notice<ref name=\"SESSp\">{{cite web |title=Alerta de Publicidad |url=http://www.sirvoes.sep.gob.mx/sirvoes/jspAvisosFull.jsp |publisher=Subsecretaria de Educacion Superior |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> stating that degrees lacking RVOE (Official Recognition from the Mexican Government) will not be validated by the SEP. Degrees via online or distance learning issued by foreign institutions like Bircham University will not be recognized by the SEP.\n\nIn April 2008 the ''Nairobi Business Daily'' reported that Bircham International University was operating in Kenya without authorization.<ref name=\"SESSp \" /> In March 2010 the same newspaper published a correction, stating that BIU \"is a Spanish institution of distance learning and is in good standing with Spanish authorities that offers alternatives to formal adult higher education specifically aimed at adult working professionals\" and that its programs \"can be legalized and validated by the Embassy of Kenya in the USA or Spain despite the institution not being registered by the Commission for Higher Education in Kenya\".<ref name=\"BDailNairobi\">{{cite news |last=Nairobi |first=Mwaura Kimani |title=Kenya: Queries Over Quality of Degrees Awarded By Spanish College |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200804140057.html |access-date=29 May 2014 |newspaper=Business Daily |date=13 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906152746/http://allafrica.com/stories/200804140057.html |archive-date=6 September 2008}}</ref> An official of Kenya's Commission for Higher Education was quoted as warning that BIU degree certificates would not be recognized.<ref name=\"BusiensDailyCOrrect\">{{cite news |title=Bircham International University \u2013 Correction and Clarification |url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Company%20Industry/-/539550/875402/-/t2qw1gz/-/index.html |access-date=29 May 2014 |newspaper=Business Daily |date=8 March 2010}}</ref> In 2013, BIU directors state that BIU does not have any presence in Kenya nor any collaboration with other any college or educational institution in Kenya.<ref name=\"ZegabiEANKenya \" />\n\nIn 2013, health fraud activist [[Stephen Barrett]] conducted a review concluding: \"BIU offers what amounts to supervised textbook reading plus credentials that suggest bearers have considerably more formal education and expertise than they actually have. The requirements for its degrees are much less than those of universities accredited by CHEA-recognized agencies. Most of BIU's teachings are straightforward, but some promote pseudoscientific concepts and practices. None of its health-related programs\u2014by themselves\u2014provide an adequate basis for clinical practice.\"<ref name=\"QuackQuestionable\">{{cite web |last=Barrett |first=Stephen |title=Questionable Organizations: An Overview |url=http://www.quackwatch.org/04ConsumerEducation/nonrecorg.html |publisher=Quackwatch |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"CredentialWatchBarrett\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.bircham.edu/ Bircham International University}}\n\n[[Category:Unaccredited institutions of higher learning]]\n[[Category:Distance education institutions based in the Bahamas]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1992]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Globalize|1=article|2=United States|date=February 2020}}\n{{Undue weight|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name=Bircham International University\n|image=File:Bircham-University.jpg\n|established=1992\n|city=[[Madrid]]\n|country=[[Spain]]\n|type=[[Educational accreditation|Unaccredited]] distance learning\n|president=Deric Bircham\n|vice-president=Laurence Cheng Wen\n|head_label=CEO\n|head=William Martin\n|website={{URL|http://www.bircham.edu}}\n}}\n[[File:Bircham International University Madrid Office.jpg|thumb|Bircham International University office in Madrid]]\n\n'''Bircham International University''' is a private, [[educational accreditation|unaccredited]]<ref name=\"ODA2013\">{{cite news |url=http://www.oregonstudentaid.gov/oda-degree-authorization-academic-unauthorized-Invalid.aspx |title=Unauthorized Schools and Invalid Degrees |publisher=[[Oregon State Office of Degree Authorization]] |access-date=4 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509021211/http://oregonstudentaid.gov/oda-degree-authorization-academic-unauthorized-Invalid.aspx |archive-date=9 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MainDepartLisAcr\">{{cite web |title=List of Non-Accredited Post-Secondary Schools |url=http://www.maine.gov/doe/highered/nonaccredited/list/b.html |publisher=Maine Department of Education |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref>\ninstitution of [[distance-learning]] higher education. It is registered in [[Spain]] and [[Delaware]], and formerly operated from [[the Bahamas]].<ref name=\"Delaware3169search\">{{cite web |title=Delaware Company Search 3169257 |url=https://delecorp.delaware.gov/tin/GINameSearch.jsp |publisher=Delaware.gov |access-date=29 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106214416/https://delecorp.delaware.gov/tin/GINameSearch.jsp |archive-date=6 January 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBIU was founded by Deric Bircham, William Martin, and Bircham's adopted son, Laurence Cheng Wen.<ref name=\"CredentialWatchBarrett\">{{cite web |last=Barrett |first=Stephen |title=A Skeptical Look at Bircham International University |url=http://www.credentialwatch.org/reports/bircham.shtml |publisher=Credential Watch |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> According to its website,<ref name=\"BIULegalHistory\">{{cite web |title=BIU Legal History |url=http://www.bircham.us/foundations/biu-legal-history.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226035457/http://www.bircham.us/foundations/biu-legal-history.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 December 2013 |publisher=BIU Forum |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> Bircham was established in Europe in 1992<ref>{{cite book |last1=Seneca |first1=Kristofer |title=Guide to Earning Law and Law-Related Degrees Nontraditionally |date=2009 |publisher=Lulu |isbn=978-0-557-10593-9<!-- |access-date=27 June 2014-->}}</ref> and is also registered in Delaware (United States), Spain, and the Bahamas. [[John Bear]], authority on [[distance education]], wrote in the 2003 edition of ''Bears' Guide to Earning Degrees by Distance Learning'' that Bircham's listed \"delegation addresses [are] in Spain, England, United States (a [[Mail Boxes Etc.]] in Miami, Florida), Bahamas, Taiwan, China, Mexico, Argentina, Venezuela, Ecuador, Peru, Bolivia, Columbia, and New Zealand.\" ''Bear's Guide'' states that \"the offices in England and the Bahamas were strictly administrative and did not serve students.\"<ref name=\"bear\">{{cite book|last=Bear|first=John|url=|title=Bears' Guide to Earning Degrees by Distance Learning|date=2003|publisher=Ten Speed Press|isbn=1-58008-431-1|location=|page=}}<!--|access-date= 7 July 2015--></ref>\n\nBircham acquired  Oxford International College in 2000.<ref name=\"BirchRevisted\">{{cite web |last=Bear |first=John |title=Bircham International University revisited |url=http://www.degreeinfo.com/general-distance-learning-discussions/45894-bircham-international-university-revisited.html |publisher=Degree Info |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"OxfordUK\">{{cite web |title=Oxford International College in the UK |url=http://www.bircham.net/uk-companies-house.html |publisher=BIU Human Network |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Oxford College Dissolved |url=http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk |website=UK Companies House |access-date=2 November 2014 |location=3656298}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation status ==\n\nBIU's website presents a list of accreditations and memberships,<ref name=\"BIUworldreferences\">{{cite web |title=Bircham International University World References |url=http://www.bircham.net/biu-references/world-references.html |publisher=BIU Human Network |access-date=29 May 2014}}</ref> but none of them are from an educational accreditation body recognized by the countries where it operates.<ref name=\"ODA2013 \" />{{better source|date=